Motivation

One of the most useful kinds of data we can collect to benefit the safety of cities in our country is crime data. From data recorder by police forces, we can learn about what types of crime are most common in certain areas, which locations in a city are more prone to crime, what types of peope are arrested as perpetrators of crime and victims, and so much more. This allows residents of cities to better choose safe places to reside and protect themselves from crime. It also helps local government and police departments make smarter decisions in legislation on various types of crime and community resources to prevent it.

Additionally, a stay at home order has been in place for several months now, meaning that most Angelinos have been in their homes all day. This may have an impact on crime demographics and trends and we will alayze this. One could also hypothesize that because there is less outdoor activity, and more people at home guarding their belongings, there may be a decrease in certain types of crime such as burglary or vandalism. Fortunately, we have the data and tools we need to test these hypotheses.

In this tutorial, I will be analyzing and creating visualizations of a dataset describing crime reports from January 2020 to May 4th, 2020, from Los Angeles, California the second largest city in the United States. The dataset I am using can be found here https://data.lacity.org/A-Safe-City/Crime-Data-from-2020-to-Present/2nrs-mtv8. From this link, we can also find descriptions of each attribute which will be necessary to analyze the data. For example, the data uses the abbreivation Rpt Dist No which we can find from the description is a four-digit code representing the district in which the crime was reported.

Tidying the Data

Our next step is to tidy the data. We already have a rectagnular dataset, meaning each attribute forms a column and each entity forms a row. So, we can start by referencing the dataset source to decide which attributes/columns we want to keep for our analysis and which columns are not significant to the results or observations we want to obtain. We can then use the pipeline syntax %>% to filter each altered dataframe into the original dataframe. We can store the columns we want to keep in a vector (list of names of the attributes) and use it in the select() function to limit our dataframe to only include the necessary columns. By limiting the number of attributes, we make loading the data and running queries much more efficient. We can also arrange it to view the dataframe by different attributes, such as the area in which the crime occurred occured as I did in this example.

necessary_cols <- c("DATE.OCC", "TIME.OCC","AREA.NAME", "Crm.Cd.Desc", "Vict.Age", 
                    "Vict.Sex", "Vict.Descent", "Premis.Desc", "Weapon.Desc", "LOCATION",
                    "LAT", "LON")

crimedata <- full_crimedata %>%
  select(necessary_cols) %>%
  arrange(AREA.NAME)

We may also want to tidy some of the data in certain columns. For example, the attribute describing the date the crime occurred includes a time as well, but every time is represented as 12:00 am. This is probably a standardized string added to the end of the date by whichever tool was used to report the date. It is not useful for our analysis so we can alter the column using the command gsub() to not include it. More info on gsub can be found at http://www.endmemo.com/program/R/gsub.php.

We can further clean up this dataset by renaming the headers so that they are easier to interpret using the R function colnames(). There are also many empty cells in this dataset, which we will replace with the standard represention for missing data, NA.

crimedata$DATE.OCC <- gsub("12:00:00 AM","", crimedata$DATE.OCC)

colnames(crimedata) <- c("date_occ", "time_occ", "area", "crime_desc", "victim_age",
                        "victim_sex", "victim_ethn", "premise", "weapon", "street_add", "lat", "lng")
# replace all missing data with NA
crimedata[crimedata==""] <- NA

Exploratory Data Analysis

Which Area in Los Angeles is Most Prone to Crime (arrests)?

Now, we can use this new dataframe to create a simple graph mapping where the most crimes occur in Los Angeles. We first have to create a pipeline that will group the data by each Los Angeles area, and then create a new variable named num_arrests by using the n() function to count the number of entries (arrests) for each area.

Next, we can create a plot to using the ggplot function from the tidyverse library. More on the ggplot function can be found here https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ggplot.html. Because the labels on the x axis overlap, we have to perform some extra formatting with the theme() function.

crimedata_areaplot <- crimedata %>%
  group_by(area) %>%
  summarize(num_arrests = n())
  
plot <- ggplot(crimedata_areaplot) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=area, y=num_arrests),stat="identity") + ggtitle("Number of Arrests in Los Angeles Areas in 2020")

plot <- plot + theme(axis.text.x =
                   element_text(size  = 10,
                                angle = 45,
                                hjust = 1,
                                vjust = 1))
plot

From this plot, we can see that the 2 districts with the most arrests in 2020 are the 77th Street and Central area! This observation is integral in the LAPDs decisions on where to allocate resources.

We can also visualize the data using the leaflet library (https://rstudio.github.io/leaflet/) to demonstrate data about victims from the reports. This can show us information about who is in the most danger in Los Angeles. In this map, female victims are labelled pi

paletteS <- colorFactor(c("pink", "purple"), domain = c("M", "F")) 

la_map <- leaflet(crimedata) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  setView(lat=34.05, lng=-118.24, zoom=11) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    radius = 5,
    color = ~paletteS(victim_sex),
    stroke = FALSE, fillOpacity = 0.2
  ) %>%
   addLegend("bottomleft", pal = paletteS, values = ~victim_sex, title = "Sex by Color", opacity = 1)
la_map
How Has the Stay At Home Order Affected Crime in Los Angeles?

Next, we want to look at the number of arrests by month. This will be a good start to exploring our hypothesis that crime trends may change after the stay at home order was announced. We can do this by utilizing the date column and lubridate date/time library (https://lubridate.tidyverse.org/) to gather the month of each crime report.

Since the data from the month of May is incomplete, we should not include this data in our analysis. We can remove May data using the filter() command.

# 
crimedata <- crimedata %>%
  mutate(month = month(mdy(date_occ)))


# create month groups and count number of arrests for each month
crimedata_monthplot <- crimedata %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(num_arrests = n())
  
# create bar
plot <- ggplot(crimedata_monthplot) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=month, y=num_arrests),stat="identity") +ggtitle("Los Angeles Arrests by Month in 2020")

plot

We can see from this plot that crime seems to have decreased over time throughout the year.

Hypothesis Testing and Linear Regression Analysis

We can gain more accurate results by performing a linear regression analysis between time and number of arrests. We can so this using the lm function and capture the relationship between the months of 2020 labelled in ascending order, and the number of arrests.

fit <- lm(formula = month~num_arrests, data = crimedata_monthplot)

broom::tidy(fit)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term         estimate std.error statistic p.value
##   <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  6.49     1.34           4.84  0.0168
## 2 num_arrests -0.000254 0.0000924     -2.75  0.0707

In the graph, there appeared to be a correlation between the month and number of crime reports, and our linear regression shows us that there is a statistically singificant relationship. We know this because the P value is approximately 0.01, which is less than 0.05 meaning we reject the null hypothesis.

Conclusion

In this tutorial, we have imported and tidied the Los Angeles Crime dataset from 2020 and we have found a relationship between the increased quarantine regulations and crime in Los Angeles. Now that we know crime trends have changed in Los Angeles after the stay at home orders, in future research, we could perform more linear regressions to analyze what types of crimes have increased or decreased after stay at home orders.
